        <h1 class="fable-title">The Boy Who Cried "Bug!"</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">A Tale of False Alarms, Foolish Pride, and Fatal Exploits</p>
        
        <div class="icons">üë¶üêõüö®‚ùåüò±</div>
        
        <div class="narrator-intro">
            <strong>NARRATOR:</strong> In a sleepy tech village called Debug Hollow‚Äîwhere the Wi-Fi was spotty and the coffee was strong‚Äîlived a young coder named Billy Byte. Now, folks, this ain't your grandma's shepherd story; this is Rocky and Bullwinkle territory, so expect puns, plot twists, and a narrator who's already regretting this gig.
        </div>
        
        <div class="fable-text">
            Billy was tasked with watching the village server flock‚Äîyou know, those woolly data sheep that graze on cloud pastures. Important work! Critical infrastructure! The kind of job that actually requires, you know, paying attention.
        </div>

        <div class="narrator-aside">
            <strong>NARRATOR'S NOTE:</strong> Spoiler alert: Billy does not pay attention. If you're shocked by this development, welcome to your first fable. The rest of us saw this coming from Act One.
        </div>
        
        <div class="fable-text">
            But Billy was bored. Watching servers is like watching paint dry, except the paint occasionally needs a security patch and threatens to leak your customer database.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            So one fine Tuesday afternoon, Billy decided to spice things up:
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box">
            üö® "BUG IN THE CODE!" üö®<br>
            "MASSIVE GLITCH WOLF EATING OUR SHEEP!"
        </div>
        
        <div class="fable-text">
            The villagers came running‚Äîfarmers with firewalls, knights with debuggers, the CTO who'd been in back-to-back meetings for six hours and really didn't have time for this.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            They arrived, breathless and panicked, only to find Billy giggling at his monitor.
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-billy">BILLY:</span> "Gotcha! Just testing the alert system! Works pretty good, huh?"
        </div>

        <div class="pun-alert">
            You could say Billy was... BYTE-ing off more than he could chew! ü•Å
        </div>

        <div class="narrator-aside">
            <strong>NARRATOR:</strong> Oh, Billy, you little script kiddie. If this were a cartoon, we'd cut to commercial right about now. But we can't, so buckle up for round two.
        </div>
        
        <div class="fable-text">
            The villagers were NOT amused. The CTO glared. The lead developer muttered something about "junior devs these days." But they all trudged back to their desks, because that's what you do in Debug Hollow.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            A few days later, Billy struck again:
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box">
            üö® "BUG ALERT!" üö®<br>
            "GLITCH WOLF ATTACK! THIS IS NOT A DRILL!"
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            Again, the villagers dropped everything. The farmer abandoned his firewall logs. The knight left her debugger mid-trace. Even the mayor came huffing over, muttering about "that damn kid."
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            And once again: No bug. Just Billy, now crying with laughter.
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-billy">BILLY:</span> "April Fools... in October! Classic! You guys should've seen your faces!"
        </div>

        <div class="narrator-aside">
            <strong>NARRATOR:</strong> The mayor's face, by the way, was approaching the color of a critical error message. Just FYI.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            The mayor stepped forward, veins pulsing in his forehead:
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-villagers">MAYOR:</span> "Kid, one more false alarm and you're on stack overflow duty. PERMANENTLY. We're talking legacy code from 1987. COBOL. Fortran. Maybe even Assembly if I'm feeling extra vindictive."
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            Billy gulped. Stack overflow duty was the stuff of nightmares. But he figured he'd gotten the message across. Time to behave!
        </div>

        <div class="narrator-aside">
            <strong>NARRATOR:</strong> Narrator here. He did NOT get the message across. He did NOT behave. I hate this job.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            Then, inevitably‚Äîbecause fables gotta fable‚Äîa REAL bug struck.
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            A sneaky zero-day exploit wolf, the kind that makes security researchers wake up in cold sweats. It came slithering through the network, chomping through the server sheep like they were binary biscuits. Critical data? Gone. Backups? Compromised. The whole village infrastructure? Absolutely wrecked.
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box">
            üö® "HELP! REAL BUG!" üö®<br>
            "GLITCH WOLF! THIS TIME IT'S ACTUALLY REAL!"
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            Billy screamed into every channel. He pinged everyone. He sent emergency texts. He even tried the emergency phone tree (which nobody had updated since 2019).
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            But the villagers?
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-villagers">FARMER:</span> "Yeah, right. Fool me thrice, shame on the code."
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-villagers">KNIGHT:</span> "Not falling for it again, Billy."
        </div>

        <div class="dialogue">
            <span class="character-villagers">CTO:</span> *doesn't even read the message*
        </div>

        <div class="pun-alert">
            Billy's career was about to get... DE-BUGGED! ü•Å<br>
            <small>(Okay that one was dark. Sorry.)</small>
        </div>

        <div class="fable-text">
            By the time anyone checked Billy's alerts (three hours later, when production went down), the damage was catastrophic. The data flock was decimated. Customer information? Leaked. Company reputation? Destroyed. Billy's employment status? Let's just say he's intimately familiar with COBOL now.
        </div>

        <div class="narrator-aside">
            <strong>NARRATOR:</strong> And that's how the village lost its data flock, its customers, and probably its Series B funding. On the plus side, they learned a valuable lesson about alert fatigue! Silver linings, people!
        </div>

        <div class="moral-section">
            <div class="moral-title">üìú THE MORAL üìú</div>
